      <bioghist id="aspace_bf8dc50350ccb98febeabac6635b3a40">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Nathaniel Hurd (1730-1777) was born in Boston and learned the metalsmithing trade from his father, Jacob Hurd. In addition to silversmith, he was an accomplished engraver and heraldic artist, producing numerous armorial bookplates in addition to other commercial printing.</p>
         <p>Reference:</p>
         <p>French, Hollis. <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>Jacob Hurd and His Sons Nathaniel &amp; Benjamin, Silversmiths, 1702-1781</part>
            </title>. Walpole Society, 1939.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_f6b5eebd247ff9053a1c11ae39d80012">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection contains early American bookplates designed and engraved by Nathaniel Hurd (1730-1777), a silversmith and engraver born in Boston. His armorial bookplate designs are in the Jacobean and Chippendale styles, following the English fashion.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_30184a092aa6cd0e5fd90688d1ac3508">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into two series: I. Bookplates. II. Ephemera.</p>  
      </arrangement>
